 bound people to power holders and killing groups. People joined and continued to participate in the genocide over time, Fujii shows, because killing in large groups conferred identity on those who acted destructively. The perpetrators of the genocide produced new groups centered on destroying prior bonds by killing kith and kin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnic conflictxRwanda. 0aEthnic conflictzRwanda. 0aGenocidexRwanda. 0aGenocidezRwanda. 0aHutu. 0aPolitical violencexRwanda. 0aPolitical violencezRwanda. 0aRuanda. 0aTutsi. 0aViolencexRwanda. 0aViolencezRwanda. 0aVölkermord. 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aAfrican Studies.  aHutu.  aRwanda.  aRwandan genocide.  aTutsi.  aafrican anthropology .  aafrican ethnic relations.  aafrican history .  aafrican politics .  acivil violence.  aethnic relations .  aethnicity studies .  agenocide studies .  agenocide.  ahutu killed.  akilling kith.  aliterature on the Rwandan genocide.  apower politics .  arace studies .  arwandan genocide.  arwandan history .  athe order of genocide .  aunderstanding genocide .  aviolence in Rwanda.  aviolence in society .  aviolence studies .08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145861340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801458613423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801458613/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles